AUTHOR: Pope St. Gregory the Great (540-604). METER: Sapphio and Adonic. TRANSLACPION, a cento from The Hymner, in the meter of the original. The translation has been altered to adapt it to the Roman Breviary Text. There are about twenty translations. LITURGIOAL Usu: Matins hymn from the third Sunday after Pentecost till the Sun- day nearest the Calends of October. This is the companion hymn of Ecce jam noctis, No. 10.

1. “Rising by night, let us all keep watch and ever de- vote our minds to psalmody‚ and with harmonious voices let us sing sweet hymns to the Lord.'' Psalmis.- The Psalms constitute the principal part of the Divine Offioe. They are so arranged in the Psalter that the 150 Psalms are said each week,

2. “That singing to the loving King, together with His Saints‚ we may merit to enter the royal court of heaven, and with them enjoy eternal life.''

3. “May the Blessed Deity of the Father‚ Son, and like- wise of the Holy Spirit, whose glory resounds throughout the whole world, grant us this.”
